│ StrengthenNoWrapFlags -> getAddExpr -> createSCEV -> getSCEV ->               │
│ LoopGuards::collectFromPHI -> ...\nThis indicates uncontrolled mutual         │
│ recursion between loop guard collection (LoopGuards::collect /                │
│ collectFromPHI) and SCEV construction + range inference.\n\n2. Analyzing      │
│ opt's Log:\nThe minimal IR contains a loop with a PHI whose incoming value    │
│ depends on itself through an add recurrence (%2 PHI with %3 = add %2, 1).     │
│ ScalarEvolution classifies it as {0,+,1}<...>. With expensive sharpening      │
│ enabled, SCEV tries to strengthen no-wrap flags and refine ranges. During     │
│ this, applyLoopGuards(AddRec->getStart(), L) is called (seen in stack at      │
│ frame 31 repeatedly). LoopGuards::collect invokes collectFromPHI, which for   │
│ each incoming edge calls SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(i)). That call       │
│ triggers creation/inference of SCEVs, which itself triggers range queries     │
│ that again call applyLoopGuards, re-entering guard collection. Because each   │
│ guard collection starts fresh (Depth resets to 0 in LoopGuards::collect), the │
│ MaxLoopGuardCollectionDepth limit does not break the cycle. The recursion is  │
│ not tail-recursive and keeps consuming stack until a random crash in          │
│ unrelated code (here inside ConstantInt::get). This is a classic uncontrolled │
│ reentrancy scenario.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe root cause is that       │
│ LoopGuards::collectFromPHI unconditionally calls SE.getSCEV() on incoming     │
│ values while guard collection is itself part of a call chain triggered during │
│ SCEV construction/range strengthening. This reentrancy causes exponential or  │
│ unbounded recursion. The intended depth limiter (Depth <                      │
│ MaxLoopGuardCollectionDepth) only governs recursive exploration of            │
│ predecessor blocks, not reentrant top-level guard collections initiated from  │
│ nested SCEV queries.\nA safe approach is to avoid creating new SCEVs while we │
│ are already in the middle of collecting guards. Instead, guard collection     │
│ should operate only on already existing SCEVs; if none exist yet, it should   │
│ conservatively skip attempting to derive min/max rewrite rules for that       │
│ incoming value. Changing getSCEV(...) to getExistingSCEV(...) in              │
│ collectFromPHI prevents triggering further SCEV construction and associated   │
│ range queries during guard collection, thus breaking the recursion            │
│ cycle.\nThe code location: llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp lines        │
│ ~15354-15359:\n  auto S =                                                     │
│ RewriteMap.find(SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx)));\nNeeds to be  │
│ replaced with logic that uses getExistingSCEV, handles nullptr, and bails out │
│ if absent. This introduces a graceful early-exit without creating new         │
│ SCEVs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 15354-15359 in               │
│ llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp. Replace the direct call to SE.getSCEV  │
│ with getExistingSCEV and insert a null check. Example patch                   │
│ intent:\nOriginal:\n  if (RewriteMap.empty())\n    return {nullptr,           │
│ scCouldNotCompute};\n  auto S =                                               │
│ RewriteMap.find(SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx)));\n  if (S ==   │
│ RewriteMap.end())\n    return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};\nModified:\n  if  │
│ (RewriteMap.empty())\n    return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};\n  Value *IncV │
│ = Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx);\n  const SCEV *IncS =                    │
│ SE.getExistingSCEV(IncV);\n  if (!IncS)\n    return {nullptr,                 │
│ scCouldNotCompute};\n  auto S = RewriteMap.find(IncS);\n  if (S ==            │
│ RewriteMap.end())\n    return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};\nThis prevents    │
│ reentrant SCEV construction during loop guard collection.\n(If desired for    │
│ future robustness, a reentrancy flag in ScalarEvolution could be added, but   │
│ minimal fix suffices.)\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy avoiding new SCEV construction   │
│ inside LoopGuards::collectFromPHI we break the mutual recursion between guard │
│ collection and SCEV range strengthening. The fix is localized, conservative,  │
│ and does not alter semantics beyond skipping speculative min/max rewrites     │
│ when underlying SCEVs are not yet available. Expected result:                 │
│ nary-reassociate + expensive range sharpening no longer crashes on the        │
│ reproducer; stack depth remains bounded; analysis still proceeds with         │
│ existing SCEVs.\n"})                                                          │
