│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash manifests as a deep recursive stack overflow (SIGSEGV in a benign   │
│ IR utility) during ScalarEvolution analysis triggered by the nary-reassociate │
│ pass when expensive range sharpening is enabled. The repeating stack trace    │
│ pattern shows ScalarEvolution repeatedly entering:                            │
│  getRangeForAffineNoSelfWrappingAR -> getRangeRef -> getSignedRange ->        │
│ StrengthenNoWrapFlags -> getAddExpr -> createSCEV -> getSCEV ->               │
│ LoopGuards::collectFromPHI -> ...                                             │
│ This indicates uncontrolled mutual recursion between loop guard collection    │
│ (LoopGuards::collect / collectFromPHI) and SCEV construction + range          │
│ inference.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The minimal IR contains a loop with a PHI whose incoming value depends on     │
│ itself through an add recurrence (%2 PHI with %3 = add %2, 1).                │
│ ScalarEvolution classifies it as {0,+,1}<...>. With expensive sharpening      │
│ enabled, SCEV tries to strengthen no-wrap flags and refine ranges. During     │
│ this, applyLoopGuards(AddRec->getStart(), L) is called (seen in stack at      │
│ frame 31 repeatedly). LoopGuards::collect invokes collectFromPHI, which for   │
│ each incoming edge calls SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(i)). That call       │
│ triggers creation/inference of SCEVs, which itself triggers range queries     │
│ that again call applyLoopGuards, re-entering guard collection. Because each   │
│ guard collection starts fresh (Depth resets to 0 in LoopGuards::collect), the │
│ MaxLoopGuardCollectionDepth limit does not break the cycle. The recursion is  │
│ not tail-recursive and keeps consuming stack until a random crash in          │
│ unrelated code (here inside ConstantInt::get). This is a classic uncontrolled │
│ reentrancy scenario.                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The root cause is that LoopGuards::collectFromPHI unconditionally calls       │
│ SE.getSCEV() on incoming values while guard collection is itself part of a    │
│ call chain triggered during SCEV construction/range strengthening. This       │
│ reentrancy causes exponential or unbounded recursion. The intended depth      │
│ limiter (Depth < MaxLoopGuardCollectionDepth) only governs recursive          │
│ exploration of predecessor blocks, not reentrant top-level guard collections  │
│ initiated from nested SCEV queries.                                           │
│ A safe approach is to avoid creating new SCEVs while we are already in the    │
│ middle of collecting guards. Instead, guard collection should operate only on │
│ already existing SCEVs; if none exist yet, it should conservatively skip      │
│ attempting to derive min/max rewrite rules for that incoming value. Changing  │
│ getSCEV(...) to getExistingSCEV(...) in collectFromPHI prevents triggering    │
│ further SCEV construction and associated range queries during guard           │
│ collection, thus breaking the recursion cycle.                                │
│ The code location: llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp lines ~15354-15359:  │
│   auto S = RewriteMap.find(SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx)));    │
│ Needs to be replaced with logic that uses getExistingSCEV, handles nullptr,   │
│ and bails out if absent. This introduces a graceful early-exit without        │
│ creating new SCEVs.                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 15354-15359 in llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp. Replace the  │
│ direct call to SE.getSCEV with getExistingSCEV and insert a null check.       │
│ Example patch intent:                                                         │
│ Original:                                                                     │
│   if (RewriteMap.empty())                                                     │
│     return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};                                      │
│   auto S = RewriteMap.find(SE.getSCEV(Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx)));    │
│   if (S == RewriteMap.end())                                                  │
│     return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};                                      │
│ Modified:                                                                     │
│   if (RewriteMap.empty())                                                     │
│     return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};                                      │
│   Value *IncV = Phi.getIncomingValue(IncomingIdx);                            │
│   const SCEV *IncS = SE.getExistingSCEV(IncV);                                │
│   if (!IncS)                                                                  │
│     return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};                                      │
│   auto S = RewriteMap.find(IncS);                                             │
│   if (S == RewriteMap.end())                                                  │
│     return {nullptr, scCouldNotCompute};                                      │
│ This prevents reentrant SCEV construction during loop guard collection.       │
│ (If desired for future robustness, a reentrancy flag in ScalarEvolution could │
│ be added, but minimal fix suffices.)                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By avoiding new SCEV construction inside LoopGuards::collectFromPHI we break  │
│ the mutual recursion between guard collection and SCEV range strengthening.   │
│ The fix is localized, conservative, and does not alter semantics beyond       │
│ skipping speculative min/max rewrites when underlying SCEVs are not yet       │
│ available. Expected result: nary-reassociate + expensive range sharpening no  │
│ longer crashes on the reproducer; stack depth remains bounded; analysis still │
│ proceeds with existing SCEVs.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
